    {
      "id": "5a93c517_7d181c1e",
      "file_path": "common/openecomp-tosca-datatype/src/main/java/org/openecomp/sdc/tosca/datatypes/model/InterfaceDefinition.java",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": 60,
      "message": "This method conflicts with setOperations(). Meaning there are two ways to modify this.operations. And setOperations() potentially overrides anything that was previously populated via addOperation(). It's very easy to mess up in the client code. You should leave only one method for consistency - either let clients populate a map outside, or let this class control how its internal map is populated.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 329,
        "name": "Vitaly Emporopulo",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Vitaliy.Emporopulo@amdocs.com",
        "username": "vempo"
      },
      "updated": "2018-02-18 20:47:26.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "5a93c517_9d15e8e6",
      "file_path": "common/openecomp-tosca-datatype/src/main/java/org/openecomp/sdc/tosca/datatypes/model/InterfaceDefinition.java",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": 69,
      "message": "Use automatic code generation for this. First, you don't need getters as they simply return the field values. Second, using Objects.equal() could have saved you all these null checks. Compare \n\nif (!Objects.equals(this.type, that.type)) {\n    return false;\n}",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 329,
        "name": "Vitaly Emporopulo",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Vitaliy.Emporopulo@amdocs.com",
        "username": "vempo"
      },
      "updated": "2018-02-18 20:47:26.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
